About

As a Master of Public Health graduate with experience spanning legislative affairs, discrimination law, and policy research, I bring a unique intersection of public health expertise and legal-legislative acumen to addressing systemic challenges facing New York communities.

My career has been driven by a commitment to translating policy into practice and ensuring that government serves the people who need it most. From researching family leave laws at the federal level to managing constituent casework for the New York State Assembly, I've developed a deep understanding of how legislation impacts real livesâ€”and how to advocate effectively within the system.

Currently serving as a Paralegal in discrimination law, I support clients navigating complex legal challenges while honing my research, case management, and litigation support skills. My public health background provides crucial context for understanding how policy decisions affect health equity, housing access, and community well-being.
